args: (Finally, the book is complete.\nNow comes the hard part...)
(I should introduce myself to start.\nI hope written notes will suffice?)
＂I am Norwin, a picture-book author.\nIt is an honor to meet you.＂
＂I have brought you a book, sir.＂
＂A picture book for a grown man?＂
＂It is a tale called 'The Song of the Sea.'＂
Please, sir! Just read through it once!
＂I know of your unfortunate past with the\nocean—and what you lost as a result.＂
＂Reality is oft a cruel thing, and despair\na feeling I know all too well.＂
＂All the more reason I wish to ease yours.＂
＂So I ask you now, humbly, to read this\nstory through but a single time.＂

A beautiful princess who loved nothing more
than to sing once lived amongst the waves.
But one day, a terrible storm separated her
from her dearest friend.

Left alone beneath the sea, she spent each
day singing, her songs reaching none but
herself. She sang of her friend—and the love
she felt there in the calm, beautiful abyss.
Months turned to years. But one day, a magical\nthread appeared and guided her ever upward\nto the water's surface.

There, she beheld a world not seen in an age.
The night sky full of stars uncountable.
The galaxies in their shimmering dances.
It filled her heart and soul with new purpose,
and she swore then and there to find him.
＂If you are out there waiting somewhere—\nand if it can bring a smile to your face—\nthen I will sing your song eternal.＂

And so she swam the ocean wide and deep,
resolved to find her friend even if he hid within
the countless stars above, or if the sky itself
went dark and cold rain fell without pause.
＂This book is my humble attempt\nto put Siren's song to paper.＂
＂My attempt to help her song\nreach you one last time.＂
＂Siren? I believe that is your cue.＂
I've missed you so, SO much!
I so badly wanted to see you.\nAnd to apologize.
It's all my fault, what happened to you.\nAll of it. I'm so sorry.
No it isn't, Paul. It really isn't.\nBesides, none of that matters now!
I should have gone looking for you.\nEvery time I saw water, I thought of you.
Then I'd think how I'd never hear you sing\nagain and...and it tore me apart.
So you decided to hide here,\naway from the shore?
I was too weak, Siren. I knew what they\nwere saying. Those terrible rumors.\n...But I couldn't stop them.
None of that matters anymore, Paul.\nI'm just so happy to be with you again.
Oh, and I came here to bring a smile to\nyour face, so let's see it already!
＂Even if I can no longer hear it,\nyour song still echoes in my ears.＂
＂This picture book brought that back to me.\nThank you for your wonderful creation.＂
You did it, Norwin! You totally found a way\nto make my dream come true!
This is all thanks to the power of your\nsong; I merely wrote a book.
Okay, do NOT be like that right now.\nYou gave me a PERFECT ending!
＂I still love your song and your smile.\nNow, as ever.＂
Oh, you know it! Here's a TOTALLY snappy\nnumber to get you up on your feet!
(Reality is cruel at times: Tragedy is\nheaped on merciless tragedy until all\nthat remains is despair.)

(But tragedy and despair are not the end.
Those tales continue, and happy endings
may yet come to pass—in reality as well
as in fiction.)
(I may never be able to serve as a\nkind of hope for the hopeless as\n{player_name} does...)
(But with imagination, paint, and quill,\nI can craft my picture books.)
＂The ocean princess and her prince smiled\nwide, and both lived happily ever after.\n—The End.＂
